/*! @page Tests Testing infrastructure and test project structure
 *  @defroup Tests
 *  @brief Overview of test types, directory layout, build jobs, and migration plan.
 *
 *  @details
 *           ### Overview
 *           Draupnir tests are organized by module and by test type. The goal of this layout is:
 *           - to keep tests close to the module they validate;
 *           - to support both local runs and CI runs using the same test targets;
 *           - to allow grouping tests into different jobs without changing leaf test projects;
 *           - to reserve a dedicated place for future compilation-only tests.
 *
 *           The recommended test categories are:
 *           - `unit` — small isolated tests for individual classes, functions, utilities, and template components;
 *           - `integration` — tests that validate interaction between several classes, subsystems, or modules;
 *           - `compilation` — compile-only tests, including both "must compile" and "must fail with expected error"
 *             scenarios.
 *
 *           ### Directory layout
 *           Tests should remain grouped by module. Each module may contain its own test tree with the following structure:
 *           @code{.txt}
 *           tests/
 *             common/
 *               TestDefaults.pri
 *               ...
 *
 *             jobs/
 *               AllTests.pro
 *               CoreTests.pro
 *               GuiTests.pro
 *
 *             build/
 *               <JobName>/
 *                 bin/
 *                 results/
 *                 <TestName>/
 *                   obj/
 *                   moc/
 *                   rcc/
 *                   ui/
 *
 *             <module_name>/
 *               <ModuleName>Tests.pro
 *               unit/
 *                 <TestName>/
 *                   <TestName>.pro
 *                   <TestName>.cpp
 *               integration/
 *                 <TestName>/
 *                   <TestName>.pro
 *                   <TestName>.cpp
 *               compilation/
 *                 <TestName>/
 *                   <TestName>.pro
 *                   <TestName>.cpp
 *           @endcode
 *
 *           ### Leaf test projects
 *           Each individual test project should be intentionally small and simple.
 *
 *           A leaf `*.pro` file should only:
 *           - include shared test defaults;
 *           - include required draupnir-lib module `*.pri` files;
 *           - include optional test helpers or mocks;
 *           - declare its own sources.
 *
 *           A leaf `*.pro` file should not:
 *           - define global job orchestration logic;
 *           - duplicate common compiler or Qt configuration;
 *           - hardcode build layout unrelated to the current test target.
 *
 *           Typical example:
 *           @code{.pri}
 *           include(../../../common/TestDefaults.pri)
 *           include(../../../../modules/Containers.pri)
 *
 *           SOURCES += \
 *               FixedMapTest.cpp
 *           @endcode
 *
 *           ### Shared test defaults
 *           Common test configuration should be moved into `tests/common/TestDefaults.pri`.
 *           This file should contain configuration shared by most test executables, for example:
 *           @code{.pri}
 *           QT += testlib
 *           CONFIG += console testcase c++20
 *           TEMPLATE = app
 *
 *           TARGET = $$basename(PWD)
 *           @endcode
 *
 *           Additional flags or paths may be added later if they are truly common across most tests.
 *
 *           ### Test jobs
 *           Files in `tests/jobs/` are orchestration projects. They do not define test logic themselves.
 *           Instead, they define which test targets belong to a specific run, for example:
 *           - all fast core tests;
 *           - GUI-related tests;
 *           - compilation-only checks;
 *           - full test suite.
 *
 *           A job is expected to control its own build output directory, for example:
 *           @code{.txt}
 *           tests/build/<JobName>/bin
 *           tests/build/<JobName>/results
 *           @endcode
 *
 *           This makes local execution and CI integration easier, because one job corresponds to one set of binaries
 *           and one set of results.
 *
 *           ### Naming conventions
 *           It is recommended to use one consistent naming scheme for test directories, project files, and targets.
 *           For example:
 *           - `FixedMapTest`
 *           - `MessageSystemIT`
 *           - `TypeListCompile`
 *
 *           The directory name, `*.pro` file name, and resulting target name should match whenever possible.
 *
 *           ### Compilation tests
 *           Compilation tests are a first-class test category and should live next to `unit` and `integration`.
 *           They are intended for scenarios such as:
 *           - code must compile successfully;
 *           - code must fail to compile;
 *           - compiler diagnostics must contain an expected message.
 *
 *           The actual validation of expected compiler output is not a responsibility of qmake itself and should be
 *           implemented by dedicated wrapper scripts. However, the directory structure should reserve a stable place
 *           for such tests from the start.
 *
 *           ### Local runs and CI
 *           The same test executables should be usable both locally and in CI.
 *           The build system should therefore focus on:
 *           - predictable target names;
 *           - predictable output directories;
 *           - minimal duplication in leaf test projects.
 *
 *           Formatting of reports, HTML generation, parsing compiler errors, and similar tasks should be implemented
 *           by runner scripts or CI logic on top of the produced test binaries.
 *
 *           ### Current migration direction
 *           The current repository already contains module-based tests and shared test helpers. The target state is an
 *           incremental cleanup rather than a full rewrite. Existing tests can be migrated gradually. */
